snippet.textDisplay:
"You don't have to have the next 20 years of your life figured out"
damn i needed that.
a couple days ago, my family started pushing med-school onto me because, i quote, "it's the only career that is not going to massively change in the next decades, the ONLY CAREER that can guarantee a future", because jobs keep appearing and dissapearing, all of that. But I don't have a single drop of personality/interest in any medical area. And my family kept shutting down everything i wanted to pursue, be it with my drawings, in administration, in languages, because "there is no guarantee of this career existing 15, 20 years in the future.
I'm only 18. I JUST figured out what i really wanted and I am going after it, I have this year planned and that's a first time in my life i really, truly have a schedule I want to follow. I couldn't think of what to do with my life next month, why would I be thinking about the next 20 years? I can die tomorrow for all I know.
but the pressure to think about the future, to have your life planned, even knowing that the people who tell me that doesn't even have their own lifes in the line, kicks my chair all the time. It's the one constant in my life these last years.

So to hear that i don't have to think too far into the future from someone older, with more experience, from someone I truly admire and respect like Jack, really makes me feel a little better about my inhability to think of what may happen next year.
Thanks for that, Jack. Keep up the good work, with the community and with yourself. Take care, everyone.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't know if you'll see this and I'm sure you see a lot of comments like this, but Jack I just want to say;
I know all too well what it's like to have depression. The way you described yourself in that time is me every other day. I've talked to people, I have medication, but it doesn't always help.
I get severe separation anxiety as well where I hate to be alone and it sends me down further. It's a hard battle that isn't easy to fight, but I'm still here. And I'm so proud of you for opening up about your depression. It's not an easy thing to do often.

With that said, your PMA motivation has helped me. If I'm having a hard time, I'll come watch you. Your PMA has become a big thing in my life and helps me be like "okay. I can do better. I can try my best and be alright."

I thank you for being yourself and bringing joy and laughter to so many people. I hope some day I can meet you and give you a hug and just tell you what a special person you are. Though can't promise I won't cry. Have a wonderful day Sean. :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Oof.
Been following you for a few years now man, and often wished we could be friends, just as people, away from the celebrity and prejudice, and the happy acts we feel we have to put on some days... genuinely think we would get along.
Gab too, which is why I was super happy for you both when you got together. You guys are a great match.
It's actually been real interesting seeing the contrast with you both when you play together -- such different styles and comfort levels with silence etc.
You guys can learn a lot from each other, and really balance each other out in real life. (I mean this in a good way - it's the same way in my own relationship!)

I'm just sorry you have to put up with so much, and people not treating you as a person...it can so easily lead you to not thinking you can even have feeling or behave like a real person.
That's some unhealthy pressure, for the workplace and outside it...

Anyway, cool of you to share so much with us.
We love ya, man!

snippet.textDisplay:
“You’ve got to be a little selfish”

This could just be from personal experience, but I feel like this is one of the most important lessons anyone can learn.
Being selfish is painted as such a bad thing, but it’s important to be a little selfish. If you’re like me and you tend to think of others first and you just want to be kind and help people, that can backfire on you when a toxic person takes advantage of you.
I was in a toxic manipulative relationship for two years and it took being selfish and thinking of myself for once to drag myself out of it.
It’s so important to think about your own well being first, even if there are others who perceive that as bad.

snippet.textDisplay: I agree talk to people, I had those thoughts, and unfortunately for me it almost happened, and in October 12th 2013, I was about to take my own life, I snuck in to a multistorey apartment in Eastbourne, got to the roof and started to make my way to the edge, but I couldn't do it, I was standing on the edge and I was thinking about my parents, my friends, and the rest of my family, how would they feel about if I died? Do I really want my life to end this way deep down? I stepped back from the edge, fell down to my knees and brawled my eyes out, I cried for a good 30 to 40 mins, I started to think, I don't want to die, I want the thoughts I was felling to stop, so I did the only thing I could, I went to a counselor, I was able to get a walk in session. And I started to feel better he told me he was gonna help me, we exchanged emails and got home, before my parents and my sister were back to read my suicide note, they still don't know and I don't want to worry them so I haven't told them to this day, and after a few more sessions, my life got better and I no longer felt depressed. So remember if you're feeling depressed to the point you feel like suicide is your only option. Remember this you don't want to kill yourself, you want the pain to stop.

snippet.textDisplay:
Dear Jack,
I've been in a rut for a while now. Sometimes I sit and have those deep dark thoughts for hours on end. I've recently come across a quote that's been keeping me afloat. "When you're depressed you don't control your thoughts, your thoughts control you." -Iprevail. It's hard to have all the pressure of all these people expecting you to cheer them up or make them smile during the bad times. If you need a break we'll all understand. We all love you. I'm very sorry that you had those thoughts. It's very hard to come back from that point in your life. I'm very glad that you have so many people that love you and are here for you.

snippet.textDisplay: My dad passed from lung cancer last year.   He was such a great man: so funny, so happy, well loved, & the best dad a person could ask for.  Now the pain never goes away w/o him here & there are times where I cant breathe from the sadness.   But there are days where I watch your channel & for a brief amount of time, I can smile or laugh from your videos.  I just want to say thank you.  Its ppl like you who, with your positivity,  funny demeanor & kindness reminds ppl like myself, that the world isnt always sad or disappointing & theres life & happiness beyond the immediate thing that's going wrong.  So thanks again.  I dont know how I found your channel but I'm really glad I did.

snippet.textDisplay: A lot of people disassociate from their pain, bad things going on in the world, from the pain of others and they put on a mask to pretend they are happy. The only way we can ever heal, is to burst that bubble and let people that we love and who love us, in. Share with them the reality of our lives, how we really feel and do our best to help each other through it. And if you don't feel like you have anyone you love or can trust, call your doctor, seek group therapy or counseling....let someone in. Because? We all truly deserve to be healthy body, heart, mind & spirit and to know true happiness.
